<p>
The Water and Environmental Hub project is creating an open source web platform that will aggregate, federate, and connect water data and information enabling users to access, mashup, analyze, model and interpret water data, information, issues and opportunities. By combining water expertise, an open web development approach¸ along with an entrepreneurial foundation, the project will spur economic diversification and benefit both public users and the private sector by improving access to water data, information, and tools for academia, government, industry, NGOs, and the general public.
</p>

<p>
In partnership with other open data repositories around water, the WEHUB is developing a web-based platform that will not only provide a water-related data catalogue, but deliver an innovative aggregator service that is linked with a unified output service (API). This will allow organizations and users to develop customized applications on top of the WEHUB web platform and gain access to all of the WEHUB's aggregated data.
</p>

<p>
In terms of geographical scope, the project will begin with southern Alberta water data and information, a region to which the partners have relevant expertise and networks. As development successes are achieved, the project is expected to extend across Alberta and Western Canada, with scalability a key design thrust.
</p>

<p>
The WEHUB will be structured as a three-tiered system with a Client, Server and Database.  Each tier in the system will be divided into components that address the catalogue, spatial and non-spatial data, and the social network requirements.  The catalogue will act as the index for the data and will allow for easy search, download and upload of the data. The spatial data will be shown on the client - as a map - making it easy for the user to visualize the data.  The social network will allow for commenting, flagging and sharing of data. The WEHUB will employ a Representational State Transfer (REST) software architecture. Open standards (e.g. OGC standards such as WMS, WFS, SOS, waterML, groundwaterML, etc.) will be used whenever practical, efficient and economical to meet the needs of users.
</p>

<p>
This two year (2010-12), $1.8 million project is funded by Western Economic Diversification, the University of Lethbridge, and Cybera Inc. The project is driven by  the University of Lethbridge, Cybera Inc., and the Alberta WaterPortal. Tesera Systems and Dr. Steve Liang (GeoSensor Web Lab) are the lead developers for the project.
</p>

<h2>Vision</h2>
<p>
To become the open source, web platform that connects water and environmental data with the tools and people needed to advance water research, integrated management, innovation, and economic diversification.
</p>

<h2>Mission</h2>
<p>
To make all water and environmental data and information freely open and accessible via the web, freeing resources previously consumed by searching for and acquiring data, thereby enabling new water perspectives and accelerating water research, integrated management, innovation, and economic diversification.
</p>

